<TITLE> Myanmar junta extends curfew in north Yangon </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 YANGON, Sept 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Myanmar's military junta extended a night-time curfew on Friday in a restive district of north Yangon where eight people were reported killed by soldiers in protests a day earlier. Witnesses said crowds of protesters were gathering in South Okkalapa district despite the presence of troops and riot police and broadcasts from loudspeaker trucks announced a curfew from 6 p m to 6 a m. The whole of Yangon and Mandalay, the former Burma's second city, were placed under a 9 p m to 5 a m curfews on Tuesday in a bid to quell the biggest anti-junta protests in nearly 20 years. The Asia Human Rights Commission said eight people were shot dead in the Okkalapa area during a crackdown on Thursday on thousands of people protesting against 45 years of military and intensifying economic hardship. Citing a source in the city, the Hong Kong-based group said bodies of the victims were taken to houses in the neighbourhood but security forces searched the area and took them aw
